Q2

sales_date_range <- sales %>% 
  summarise(minDate = min(Date),
            maxDate = max(Date) ,
            date_range_days = maxDate - minDate +6) %>% 
  mutate (diff = difftime(maxDate, minDate, units = "weeks") + 1)

sales_date_range
##      minDate    maxDate date_range_days      diff
## 1 2010-02-05 2012-10-26       1000 days 143 weeks

A2: We calculated the date range by subtracting the smallest given date from the largest given date, to which we added another 6 days, as the dates indicated the first day of the week to which the data is attributed.

We joined together information from sales and stores to inspect if there was any significant correlation between store type and weekly sales or size. We found that Type A, B, C seems to be in reference to the size of the store as indicated by the boxplot above. The stores with the largest size are categorized as Type A, the medium sized stores are categorized as Type B, and the smallest sized stores are categorized as Type C.

# Histogram to look at distribution of weekly sales. Weekly sales were negative for a few weeks so we tried looking at the distribution for only positive values. 
sales %>% 
  filter(Weekly_Sales>0) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Weekly_Sales)) +
  geom_histogram() +
  #Added limits to view values around 0
  xlim(-10000,150000) +
    labs(title="Distribution of weekly sales",
       x="Weekly Sales",
       y="Count")

#Calculation log of weekly sales excluding negative weekly sales values
sales %>% 
  filter(Weekly_Sales>0) %>% 
  mutate(sales_log = log(Weekly_Sales)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=sales_log)) +
  geom_histogram() +
      labs(title="Logarithmic distribution of weekly sales",
       x="Weekly Sales (log)",
       y="Count")

The distribution of weekly sales is right skewed. We then looked at the distribution of the log of weekly sales (only focusing on positive values), which gives a left skewed distribution.

Q2 - Hypothesis test to check if there is a significant difference in weekly sales during holiday and normal weeks (excluding Thanksgiving)

# H0: There is no difference in weekly sales on holiday weeks compared to non-holiday weeks.
# v.s.
# H1: There is difference in weekly sales on holiday weeks compared to non-holiday weeks.


#Creating column with the holiday name:
holiday_sales_data <- sales %>% 
  mutate(holiday = case_when(month(Date) == 12 & IsHoliday == TRUE  ~ "Christmas", 
    month(Date) == 2  & IsHoliday == TRUE ~ "SuperBowl", 
    month(Date) == 11  & IsHoliday == TRUE ~ "Thanksgiving", 
    month(Date) == 9 & IsHoliday == TRUE ~ "LaborDay",
    TRUE ~ "non_holiday")) 

#Filtering out Thanksgiving rows
non_thanksgiving_sales <- holiday_sales_data %>%   
  filter(holiday != "Thanksgiving")

Running a t-test:

t.test(Weekly_Sales ~ IsHoliday, data = non_thanksgiving_sales)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  Weekly_Sales by IsHoliday
## t = 1, df = 26693, p-value = 0.3
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group FALSE and group TRUE is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -124  462
## sample estimates:
## mean in group FALSE  mean in group TRUE 
##               16012               15844

The t test shows that the p-value is 0.26 and t value is 1.13, which means that we fail to reject the Null hypothesis. The 95% confidence interval is [-124,462] which contains zero. It means that we cannot say that there is a significant difference in weekly sales on holiday weeks compared to non-holiday weeks if we exclude Thanksgiving as a holiday.

3 Regression Models

After analyzing the data we decided to focus on predicting the weekly sales at a store level instead of department level.

#Looking at weekly sales at a store level (instead of department)
stores_weekly_sales <- holiday_sales_data %>%
  group_by(Store,Date,IsHoliday) %>%
  summarise(sum_weekly_sales = sum(Weekly_Sales))

#Joined sales, stores and details and mutated Store column to be numeric for purposes of running the regression model
model_data <- stores_weekly_sales %>%
  left_join(details, by=c("Store","Date","IsHoliday")) %>%
  left_join(stores, by="Store") %>%
  drop_na() %>%
  mutate(Store = as.numeric(Store)) %>%
  mutate(holiday = case_when(month(Date) == 12 & IsHoliday == TRUE  ~ "Christmas",
    month(Date) == 2  & IsHoliday == TRUE ~ "SuperBowl",
    month(Date) == 11  & IsHoliday == TRUE ~ "Thanksgiving",
    month(Date) == 9 & IsHoliday == TRUE ~ "LaborDay",
    TRUE ~ "non_holiday"))
# create a model with all explainatory variables
model_full <- lm(sum_weekly_sales ~ . , data= model_data)
